						<div class="article__content-body n-content-body js-article__content-body">
							<p>Economic sentiment in the UK plummeted in February to its lowest level in six years as Brexit uncertainty intensified, according to an EU survey. </p><p>The European Commission&#x2019;s monthly economic sentiment indicator for Britain dropped from 103.7 in January to 99.2 in February, the lowest since 2013 and below the bloc&#x2019;s 1990-2017 long-term average of 100.&#xA0;</p><p>The fall contrasted with sentiment remaining largely stable in the eurozone at 106.3 despite the region&#x2019;s slowing economic growth.&#xA0;The indicator measures confidence among consumers and in four business sectors: industry, services, construction and retail.</p><div class="o-ads in-article-advert advert" data-o-ads-name="mpu" data-o-ads-center="true" data-o-ads-label="true" data-o-ads-targeting="pos=mid;" data-o-ads-formats-default="MediumRectangle,Responsive" data-o-ads-formats-small="MediumRectangle,Responsive" data-o-ads-formats-medium="MediumRectangle,Responsive" data-o-ads-formats-large="Responsive" data-o-ads-formats-extra="Responsive" aria-hidden="true"></div><p>The fall in the UK&#x2019;s economic sentiment &#x201C;leaves the indicator pointing to growth more or less grinding to a halt&#x201D; said Oliver Allen, economist at Capital Economics, a consultancy.&#xA0;</p><p>The drop was largely driven by a fall among services companies. The sector&#x2019;s confidence indicator dropped to a net score of -16.2 in February from -4.9 in January. This is the lowest reading since December 2012 and by far the lowest in the EU, where the average was 7.1.&#xA0;</p><div class="n-content-layout"><figure class="n-content-picture n-content-layout__container"><picture><source media="screen and (max-width: 490px)" srcset="https://www.ft.com/__origami/service/image/v2/images/raw/http%3A%2F%2Fcom.ft.imagepublish.upp-prod-eu.s3.amazonaws.com%2F7a937806-3aa3-11e9-b72b-2c7f526ca5d0?source=next&fit=scale-down&quality=highest&width=490"><img src="https://www.ft.com/__origami/service/image/v2/images/raw/http%3A%2F%2Fcom.ft.imagepublish.upp-prod-eu.s3.amazonaws.com%2F6ce4b3a0-3aa3-11e9-b72b-2c7f526ca5d0?source=next&fit=scale-down&quality=highest&width=700" alt role="presentation" data-image-type="graphic"></picture></figure></div><p>Services account for 80 per cent of the UK economy and a similar level of national employment. A fall in confidence is seen as a worrying sign as business pessimism might translate into reduced hiring and investment.&#xA0;</p><p>The sub-components of the survey showed services employment expectations for the following three months dropping to 1.4 in February from 13.9 in January, the lowest reading since Autumn 2012. Services expectation of future demand also plummeted to a seven-year low.&#xA0;</p><p>The drop in the services sentiment is in line with the data from the CBI, the UK&#x2019;s most prominent business group. It reported service sector optimism deteriorating in the three months to February at the fastest pace since the financial crisis.&#xA0;</p>
