							<p>&#x201C;Avoiding a no-deal scenario and agreeing a deal that commands a majority in parliament and is acceptable to the EU and protects our economy, is the best way of improving sentiment&#x201D; Rain Newton-Smith, the CBI&#x2019;s chief economist, said in response to the economic sentiment indicator.&#xA0;</p><p>The commission survey refers to data collected in the first half of the month, before Theresa May, the prime minister, promised MPs a vote to extend Brexit negotiations if the current deal or a no-deal exit were both voted down. Yet, &#x201C;a three-month extension of negotiations merely prolongs the uncertainty that is prompting business to postpone investment and hiring decisions&#x201D;, said Samuel Tombs, economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics, a consultancy.&#xA0;</p><p>Confidence in the industrial sector also deteriorated to a net score -0.2 in February, from 2.3 in January, the lowest since October 2016.&#xA0;</p><div class="n-content-layout"><figure class="n-content-picture n-content-layout__container"><picture><source media="screen and (max-width: 490px)" srcset="https://www.ft.com/__origami/service/image/v2/images/raw/http%3A%2F%2Fcom.ft.imagepublish.upp-prod-eu.s3.amazonaws.com%2F5c59ff68-3aa3-11e9-b72b-2c7f526ca5d0?source=next&fit=scale-down&quality=highest&width=490"><img src="https://www.ft.com/__origami/service/image/v2/images/raw/http%3A%2F%2Fcom.ft.imagepublish.upp-prod-eu.s3.amazonaws.com%2F4b902c66-3aa3-11e9-b72b-2c7f526ca5d0?source=next&fit=scale-down&quality=highest&width=700" alt role="presentation" data-image-type="graphic"></picture></figure></div><p>Despite record-high employment rates and wages that have finally started to pick up, consumers remained pessimistic.&#xA0;</p><p>Consumer confidence improved marginally to -10.8 in February, from -11.3 in January. Despite the improvement, UK consumer confidence in February was the second-worst reading since 2013, and lower than for both the EU and the eurozone.</p><p>However, Martin Beck, economist at Oxford Economics, cautioned that sentiment indicators had overstated the economy&#x2019;s weakness in the past &#x201C;given the difficulty of separating emotion from hard economic developments in driving survey responses in times of high uncertainty&#x201D;.
